Final Project Tutorial: Bratz Statz¶

As a child I was obsessed with the Bratz, a line of fashion dolls created by MGA Entertainment. Recently, I’ve been indulging in nostalgia and trying tot see what the Bratz are up to these days, and it seems like they’re attempting to make a comeback. Now as someone who loves the Bratz, I don’t want to see them fail. So, I decided to take a look at their social media stats and see how successful their attempt at a comeback will be. To do this, I went to https://www.apify.com/ and used their Instagram and TikTok scraper to download data about every post the Bratz official account has made on these sites.

Unfortunately, this gave me way more data than I intended to work with.

Now that we have our DataFrames, we can mess with our data a bit! I want to see how many likes each post is getting and whether this number is increasing over time. This could provide a better sense of whether their social media presence is improving. More engagement on social media typically indicates more publicity and engagement for the dolls themselves. The first step was changing the time/timestamp columns for both DataFrames to actual datetime types since currently they’re just Objects. After this, I want to make sure the data is sorted by date so that our plot is accurate. What’s also not shown, is me going back and forth over whether to pick a scatter plot or a line plot for this data. Ultimately, I chose a line graph since it was easier to tell the shape of the data this way. To differentiate between the TikTok data and Instagram data, I decide to use purple for TikTok and pink for Instagram (purple and pink are prominent colors in the Bratz’s palette, so it seemed fitting). I also had to mess around with the figsize a bit since the outliers make the rest of the data harder to see.

Unfortunately, these graphs don’t tell us much. It’s normal that if we display data by individual posts that the data will fluctuate pretty often. Especially considering how unpredictable social media algorithms may be. It’s clear that a particular viral post is a huge outlier in our data. So, I want to break this data up even more. I want to see how the average number of engagement per year. If this is increasing, we can possibly get a better sense of whether their social media presence is growing over the years or not.

So, I’ve added a “year” column by taking the year from the time/timestamp column. With this year column, I want to group the columns by year and for each unique year, find the average number of likes, shares, and comments. Not shown is me running tt_df[“year”].unique() to see how many unique years there were and therefore how many averages I would be computing. This time, since there were such a small number of unique years since the Bratz TikTok account has only been posting since 2020, I decided a bar graph would do the job of presenting this data.

In [29]:
tt_df['year'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(tt_df['time']).year

tt_mean = tt_df.groupby('year', as_index=False)['likes', 'comments', 'shares'].mean()

tt_mean.plot.bar(x='year', y='likes', title="Average TikTok Likes per Year", 
                xlabel="Year", ylabel="Likes", color="purple")
tt_mean.plot.bar(x='year', y='comments', title="Average TikTok Comments per Year", 
                xlabel="Year", ylabel="Comments", color="purple")
tt_mean.plot.bar(x='year', y='shares', title="Average TikTok Shares per Year", 
                xlabel="Year", ylabel="Shares", color="purple")

As we can see, it seems like the TikTok engagement is increasing quite rapidly. I was a bit surprised that the comments and likes didn’t have the same shape. It seems that the average number of comments in 2018 surpassed the rest of the following years despite the average number of likes being the lowest. This also surprised me because unlike 2019-2021, the Bratz Instagram didn’t have post every month of the year. So for the average amount of comments to be so high indicates a possible controversy or maybe just an increase in bots. Nonetheless, it still seems that Instagram engagement is increasing. We so another jump in the average number of likes in 2021 which I would also assume is due to the comeback announcement that was posted to Instagram as well on the same day.

Now just for fun, I wanted to see which posts are the most successful on Instagram. I’ve created a new empty DataFrame for post types and created a column called “type” where I’ll store only the unique values of postType. There are only 3: Image, Sidecar, and Video. Since, I didn’t know what sidecar meant, I’ll define it super quick. It’s essentially just a album of multiple videos/images. After creating this column, I went on to create columns for both likes and comments. To fill these columns, I filtered the original dataframe for each unique post type and found the average for the number of comments and likes for each type. Not shown, is me making sure that the values were placed in the correct order by displaying the DataFrames when necessary. Since there were only three values, I decided to use a bar plot for this as well.

I guess when it comes to getting likes, sidecar posts are better. However, the comments seem to show more engagement for images.

The Bratz do a lot of collaborations as well. Typically will fashion brands or influencers. I wanted to know if a lot of their success on social media was a result of these collaborations. So, in the original DataFrame, I added a boolean column that shows whether or not another account was mentioned on a post. Then, I created another small dataFrame similar to the one in the previous dataset. First, I created a column for whether or not they collaborated with only the values True and False. Then, similar to the previous data, I filtered the original dataFrame by True and False and found the average of likes/comments for each value.

In [33]:
tt_df["collab"] = tt_df["mention"].isnull() == False
mention_df = pd.DataFrame()
mention_df["collab"] = [True, False]
mention_df["likes"] = [tt_df[tt_df["collab"] == True]["likes"].mean(), tt_df[tt_df["collab"] == False]["likes"].mean()]
mention_df["comments"] = [tt_df[tt_df["collab"] == True]["comments"].mean(), 
                          tt_df[tt_df["collab"] == False]["comments"].mean()]
mention_df.plot.bar(x='collab', y='comments', title="Average Number of TikTok Comments based on Collabs", 
                xlabel="Whether They Collabed or Not", ylabel="Comments", color="purple")
mention_df.plot.bar(x='collab', y='likes', title="Average Number of TikTok Likes based on Collabs",

Now to make a new dataframe for average likes/comments by month. This was a bit more tedious. I broke down the original TikTok dataframe into three separate dataframes filtered by year. Then, I created an empty dataframe which I filled will the months-year. These months/years are represented by integers because in order to create a regression line, the x-axis needed numerical values. So the integers are represented by [year][month]. These integers created the date column. Next, it was onto calculating average likes/comments/shares. What I originally ended up doing was trying to manually input all this data into the columns, but thankfully I caught myself. For each year, I dedicated for loops to fill in an array for likes/comments/shares averages and add them to the array. Since some months seemed to have no activity, I filled any null values with 0.

In [12]:
tt2020 = tt_df[tt_df["year"] == 2020]
tt2021 = tt_df[tt_df["year"] == 2021]
tt2022 = tt_df[tt_df["year"] == 2022]

tt_months = pd.DataFrame()
tt_months["date"] = [202007, 202008, 202009, 202010, 202011, 202012, 202101, 202102, 202103, 202104, 202105, 202106, 
                     202107, 202108, 202109, 202110, 202111, 202112, 202201, 202202, 202203, 202204, 202205, 202206,
                     202207, 202208, 202209, 202210, 202211, 202212]
# likes
likes_avg = []
for i in range(7, 13):
    likes_avg.append(tt2020[tt2020["month"] == i]["likes"].mean())
    
for i in range(1, 13):
    likes_avg.append(tt2021[tt2021["month"] == i]["likes"].mean()) 
    
for i in range(1, 13):
    likes_avg.append(tt2022[tt2022["month"] == i]["likes"].mean())
    
tt_months["likes_avg"] = likes_avg

# comments
comments_avg = []
for i in range(7, 13):
    comments_avg.append(tt2020[tt2020["month"] == i]["comments"].mean())
    
for i in range(1, 13):
    comments_avg.append(tt2021[tt2021["month"] == i]["comments"].mean()) 
    
for i in range(1, 13):
    comments_avg.append(tt2022[tt2022["month"] == i]["comments"].mean())

tt_months["comments_avg"] = comments_avg

# shares
shares_avg = []
for i in range(7, 13):
    shares_avg.append(tt2020[tt2020["month"] == i]["shares"].mean())
    
for i in range(1, 13):

Now onto the long awaited regression lines. This was where numpy and matplotlib become useful. Np.polyfit gives us the slope and intercept for our data, and to actually display the line, we need to use these values in plt.plot() which is why our dates needed to be in numerical form.

In [42]:
tt_months.plot.scatter(x="date", y="likes_avg", figsize=(10, 10), rot=90, 
                       title="Average Number of TikTok Likes per Month", xlabel="Date", 
                       ylabel="Likes (Average)", color="purple")
slope, intercept = np.polyfit(tt_months['date'], tt_months['likes_avg'], 1)
plt.plot(tt_months['date'], slope * tt_months['date'] + intercept)
plt.show()
